{"title_page": "Mustapha Boukar", "text_new": "{{short description|Algerian footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Mustapha Boukar\n| image = \n| fullname = Mustapha Boukar\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1962|11|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Oran]], [[Algeria]]\n| height = \n| currentclub = Retired\n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 1977\u20131980 | youthclubs1 = [[MC Oran]]\n| years1 = 1980\u20131982 | clubs1 = [[MC Oran]]      | caps1 = \u2013 | goals1 = \u2013\n| years2 = 1982\u20131990 | clubs2 = [[ASM Oran]]     | caps2 = \u2013 | goals2 = \u2013\n| years3 = 1990\u20131993 | clubs3 = KVK Westhoek     | caps3 = \u2013 | goals3 = \u2013\n| years4 = 1993\u20131995 | clubs4 = Eendracht Wervik | caps4 = \u2013 | goals4 = \u2013\n| years5 = 1995\u20131997 | clubs5 = [[ASM Oran]]     | caps5 = \u2013 | goals5 = \u2013\n| nationalyears1 = 1985\u20131988 | nationalteam1 = [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] | nationalcaps1 = 8 | nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2 = 1989      | nationalteam2 = [[Algeria national futsal team|Algeria futsal]]                | nationalcaps2 = 3   | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n\n'''Mustapha Boukar''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0635\u0637\u0641\u0649 \u0628\u0648\u0643\u0627\u0631}}; born 2 November 1962 in [[Oran]]) is an [[Algeria]]n [[Association football|football]] former player and the legendary number 10 of [[ASM Oran]] nicknamed ''Paulo C\u00e9sar'' referring to the Brazilian player of the 70th ([[Paulo C\u00e9zar Caju|Paulo C\u00e9zar \"Caju\"]]). He played in [[Belgium]] between 1991 and 1993\n\n==Honours==\n* Runners-up of the [[Algerian Cup]] with [[ASM Oran]] in 1981 and 1983\n\n==External links==\n*{{FIFA|209062}}\n*[http://dzfootball.free.fr/EN/Joueurs/fiche/Boukar-Moustapha.html Player statistics] - ''dzfootball''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boukar, Mustapha}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Oran]]\n[[Category:Algerian footballers]]\n[[Category:Algeria international footballers]]\n[[Category:Algerian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Algerian expatriate sportspeople in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:ASM Oran players]]\n[[Category:MC Oran players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Mustapha Boukar\n| image = \n| fullname = Mustapha Boukar\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1962|11|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Oran]], [[Algeria]]\n| height = \n| currentclub = Retired\n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 1977\u20131980 | youthclubs1 = [[MC Oran]]\n| years1 = 1980\u20131982 | clubs1 = [[MC Oran]]      | caps1 = \u2013 | goals1 = \u2013\n| years2 = 1982\u20131990 | clubs2 = [[ASM Oran]]     | caps2 = \u2013 | goals2 = \u2013\n| years3 = 1990\u20131993 | clubs3 = KVK Westhoek     | caps3 = \u2013 | goals3 = \u2013\n| years4 = 1993\u20131995 | clubs4 = Eendracht Wervik | caps4 = \u2013 | goals4 = \u2013\n| years5 = 1995\u20131997 | clubs5 = [[ASM Oran]]     | caps5 = \u2013 | goals5 = \u2013\n| nationalyears1 = 1985\u20131988 | nationalteam1 = [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] | nationalcaps1 = 8 | nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2 = 1989      | nationalteam2 = [[Algeria national futsal team|Algeria futsal]]                | nationalcaps2 = 3   | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n\n'''Mustapha Boukar''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0635\u0637\u0641\u0649 \u0628\u0648\u0643\u0627\u0631}}; born 2 November 1962 in [[Oran]]) is an [[Algeria]]n [[Association football|football]] former player and the legendary number 10 of [[ASM Oran]] nicknamed ''Paulo C\u00e9sar'' referring to the Brazilian player of the 70th ([[Paulo C\u00e9zar Caju|Paulo C\u00e9zar \"Caju\"]]). He played in [[Belgium]] between 1991 and 1993\n\n==Honours==\n* Runners-up of the [[Algerian Cup]] with [[ASM Oran]] in 1981 and 1983\n\n==External links==\n*{{FIFA|209062}}\n*[http://dzfootball.free.fr/EN/Joueurs/fiche/Boukar-Moustapha.html Player statistics] - ''dzfootball''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boukar, Mustapha}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Oran]]\n[[Category:Algerian footballers]]\n[[Category:Algeria international footballers]]\n[[Category:Algerian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Algerian expatriate sportspeople in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:ASM Oran players]]\n[[Category:MC Oran players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Algerian footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mustapha_Boukar"}
{"title_page": "David Yates", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix=\n| name            = David Yates\n| image           = David Yates by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| imagesize       =\n| caption         = Yates at the 2016 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1963|10|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]],<ref name=\"DavidYatesEarlyLifeBAFTA\"/> [[Lancashire]]<!-- St Helens was part of Lancashire in 1963, please do not change to Merseyside -->, England\n| alma_mater      = [[University of Essex]]\n| notable_works   = [[Wizarding World|''Wizarding World'' franchise]]\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| occupation      = Filmmaker\n| years_active    = 1988\u2013present\n| spouse          = Yvonne Walcott\n| awards          = \n}}\n'''David Yates''' (born {{birth date|1963|10|08|df=y}}) is an English [[Filmmaking|filmmaker]] who has directed films, short films, and television productions.\n\nYates directed the final four films in the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' series]].<ref name=\"DGA-DavidYatesDirectorProfile\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dga.org/Craft/DGAQ/All-Articles/1001-Spring-2010/Profile-David-Yates.aspx |title=The Wizard Behind the Camera |author=Andrew Pulver |publisher=DGA Quarterly, Directors Guild of America |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"BAFTABritannia\">{{cite news|url=http://losangeles.broadwayworld.com/article/BAFTA-Honors-John-Lasseter-and-David-Yates-1130-20110628 |title=BAFTA Honors John Lasseter and David Yates 11/30 |publisher=Broadway World (Los Angeles) |date=28 June 2011 |accessdate=28 June 2011 |quote=The worldwide success of Mr. Lasseter for Walt Disney and Pixar Animation Studios and Mr. Yates's contribution to the final four parts of the \u2018Harry Potter' franchise makes them global wizards in their own right, and are delighted to honor these remarkable filmmakers with this year's Britannia Award.}}</ref> His work on the series brought him critical and commercial success along with accolades, such as the [[Britannia Awards|British Academy Britannia Award for Excellence in Directing]].<ref name=\"BAFTABritannia\"/> Yates's subsequent projects include<!-- Only list the project name and its release date. Do not add any more awards. --> ''[[The Legend of Tarzan (film)|The Legend of Tarzan]]'' and ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]'' (both 2016), and its sequel, ''[[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]'' (2018).\n\nEarly in his career, Yates directed various short films and became a television director. His credits include the six-part political thriller ''[[State of Play (TV serial)|State of Play]]'' (2003), for which he won the [[Directors Guild of Great Britain|Directors Guild of Great Britain Award for Outstanding Directorial Achievement]], the adult two-part documentary drama ''[[Sex Traffic]]'' (2004) and the [[Emmy Award]]-winning television film ''[[The Girl in the Caf\u00e9]]'' (2005).<ref name=\"DGA-DavidYatesDirectorProfile\"/><ref name=\"DavidYatesDoesItAll\"/><ref name=\"VirginMedia-DavidYates\">{{cite news|url=http://www.virginmedia.com/movies/movieextras/top10s/potter-hbp-rumours.php |title=Ten Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince facts |publisher=Virgin Media |accessdate=19 April 2011|quote=Director David Yates, one of British TV's most respected director (thanks to the drama series State Of Play)...}}</ref>\n\nYates is a founding member of [[Directors UK]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/inside-story-in-the-right-direction--the-cream-of-britains-television-directing-talent-848048.html |title=Inside Story: In the right direction \u2013 the cream of Britain's television directing talent |work=[[The Independent]] |date=16 June 2008 |accessdate=3 August 2011 |location=London}}</ref> He has had a close partnership with [[Warner Bros.]] as a director and producer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118053263.html |title=David Yates inks first-look deal with Warner Bros. |work=Variety.com |date=27 April 2012 |accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDavid Yates was born in 1963 in Lancashire, England.{{#tag:ref|Yates was born in Lancashire, 1963, and was raised in the village of Rainhill. This was before the creation of the [[Metropolitan Borough of St Helens]], [[Merseyside]] in April 1974, in which Rainhill is now included.|group=\"n\"}} His parents died when he was young.<ref name=\"DavidYatesCollider2011\">{{cite news| url=https://collider.com/david-yates-interview-harry-potter-deathly-hallows-part-2/101507/?replytocom=155909#respond |title=Exclusive: Director David Yates Talks HARRY POTTER AND THE DEATHLY HALLOWS \u2013 PART 2, Deleted Scenes, Future Projects, and More |work=Collider.com |date=10 July 2011 |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> Raised in the village of [[Rainhill]], Yates was inspired to pursue a career in filmmaking after watching [[Steven Spielberg]]'s 1975 movie ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]''.<ref name=\"DavidYatesEarlyLifeBAFTA\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sthelensstar.co.uk/news/8850608.Yates_enjoys_Harry_Potter_BAFTA_honour/ |title=St Helens-born David Yates enjoys Harry Potter BAFTA honour |work=St Helens Star |date= 13 February 2011|accessdate=11 March 2011}}</ref> Yates's mother bought him a [[Super 8 film cameras|Super 8mm camera]]. He used this to shoot various films  in which his friends and family featured.<ref name=\"FilmLondon-DavidYates\"/> One such film, ''The Ghost Ship'', was shot on board the vessel where his uncle worked as a cook.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-life-features/liverpool-arts/2011/07/08/st-helen-s-born-director-david-yates-on-harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-part-2-92534-29014685/#ixzz1RapYxSNT |title=St Helens-born director David Yates on Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2 |author= Laura Davis|work=Liverpool Daily Post |date=8 July 2011 |accessdate=9 July 2011}}</ref> He attended Grange Park High School,<ref name=Star/> [[St Helens College]] and then the [[University of Essex]].<ref name=\"Yahoo!Movies-DavidYatesBio\">{{Cite news|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1807432789/bio |title=David Yates Biography |publisher=Yahoo! Movies |accessdate=4 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622012522/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1807432789/bio |archivedate=22 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sthelensreporter.co.uk/news/local/harry_potter_director_celebrates_box_office_smash_1_734230 |title=Harry Potter director celebrates box office smash |work=St Helens Reporter |date=3 August 2009 |accessdate=11 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"David Yates Casarotto\">{{cite news|url=http://www.casarotto.co.uk/assets/x/51023.pdf |title=David Yates |accessdate=16 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807145401/http://www.casarotto.co.uk/assets/x/51023.pdf |archivedate=7 August 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Yates said that he \"used to skive off college all the time\" and never expected to join university before being surprised by his A-Level exam results. While at the University of Essex, Yates formed the Film and Video Production Society.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/echofeatures/9835286.Directing_Harry_Potter_was_magic/ |title=Directing Harry Potter was Magic |work=Echo News |date=26 July 2012 |accessdate=23 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727123019/http://www.echo-news.co.uk/echofeatures/9835286.Directing_Harry_Potter_was_magic/ |archivedate=27 July 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> He graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in Government in 1987.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/event.aspx?e_id=4262 |title=Harry Potter director and Arctic explorer honoured at Graduation 2012 |work=University of Essex |date=17 July 2012 |accessdate=23 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130125213452/http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/event.aspx?e_id=4262 |archivedate=25 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Television and film career (1988\u20132005)===\n[[File:BeaconsfieldFilmStudios.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The [[National Film and Television School]], where Yates trained as a director<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nftsfilm-tv.ac.uk/who-we-are/honorary-fellows |title=Honorary Fellows |work=NFTS |accessdate=16 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020113653/http://nftsfilm-tv.ac.uk/who-we-are/honorary-fellows |archive-date=20 October 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>]]\n\nIn 1988, Yates made his first film ''When I Was a Girl'' in [[Swindon]]. The film entered the festival circuit where it was named [[San Francisco International Film Festival#Golden Gate Awards|Best Short Film]] at the [[San Francisco International Film Festival]]. It contributed towards Yates's acceptance into the [[National Film and Television School]] in 1989 and led to the [[BBC]] hiring him to direct ''Oranges and Lemons'', a short drama film in 1991. Before completing film school, he began to direct, produce and write the screenplay to the dramatic short ''The Weaver's Wife''. He also made his fourth short film, ''Good Looks'', which was presented at the [[Chicago International Film Festival]]. After graduating in 1992, Yates directed an episode of the film studies programme ''[[Moving Pictures (TV series)|Moving Pictures]]''.<ref name=\"FilmLondon-DavidYates\"/><ref name=\"Yahoo!Movies-DavidYatesBio\"/><ref name=\"NFTS-DavidYatesCourses\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nftsfilm-tv.ac.uk/index.php?module=People&type=Alumni&people_id=310&back=course&course_id=149 |title=Courses ... David Yates |work=nfts.co.uk |publisher=National Film and Television School |accessdate=4 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101218110537/http://www.nftsfilm-tv.ac.uk/index.php?module=People&type=Alumni&people_id=310&back=course&course_id=149 |archive-date=18 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.screenrush.co.uk/films/film-129567/casting/ |title=When I Was A Girl (TV)|publisher=Screen Rush |accessdate=14 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"DirectorandComposerCollaborations\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.filmscoremonthly.com/daily/article.cfm/articleID/6374/ |title=Current Composer/Director Partnerships, 2009 Edition |work=filmscoremonthly.com |publisher=Scott Bettencourt, Film Score Monthly |date=22 November 2009 |accessdate=14 March 2011 |quote=NICHOLAS HOOPER/DAVID YATES \"THE WEAVER'S WIFE\", \"GOOD LOOKS\" |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711002107/http://www.filmscoremonthly.com/daily/article.cfm/articleID/6374/ |archivedate=11 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.swindon.gov.uk/create |title=Arts and Culture, Create ... Harry Potter Connection |publisher=Swindon Borough Council |accessdate=15 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629053714/http://www.swindon.gov.uk/create |archivedate=29 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1994 to 1995, Yates directed several episodes of the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] police procedural ''[[The Bill]]'' before directing and producing three episodes of the television documentary ''Tale of Three Seaside Towns'' alongside producer Alistair Clarke. The programme followed media personalities [[Russell Grant]], [[Honor Blackman]] and [[Pam Ayres]] visiting and exploring the [[Southern England|South Coast]] towns of [[Brighton]], [[Eastbourne]] and [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/282 |title=The Tichborne Claimant |publisher=Philip Kemp, Sight and Sound |date=December 1999 |accessdate=14 March 2011 |quote=Yates, making his feature-film debut after directing television documentaries about British seaside towns... |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629071147/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/282 |archivedate=29 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myfairladythemusical.com/uk_cast_Blackman.htm|title=Cast & Creative ... Honor Blackman|publisher=My Fair Lady|accessdate=14 March 2011|quote=Honor presented a documentary for Workhouse TV/Meridian about Brighton which formed part of A TALE OF THREE SEASIDE TOWNS.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714142300/http://www.myfairladythemusical.com/uk_cast_Blackman.htm|archive-date=14 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Yates directed his fifth short film ''Punch'' before making his feature film debut in 1998 with the release of the independent historical-drama film ''[[The Tichborne Claimant (film)|The Tichborne Claimant]]''. The film, which was shown at the [[Edinburgh International Film Festival]], was written by Joe Fisher and based on the true events of the [[Tichborne Case]]. It starred [[Stephen Fry]] and [[Robert Hardy]] and was shot on location in [[Merseyside]] and on the [[Isle of Man]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/AFF066035 |title= PUNCH |publisher=British Board of Film Classification |date= 9 February 1996|accessdate=14 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.moviestation.org/movie/67407/The_Tichborne_Claimant |title= Movie: The Tichborne Claimant |publisher=Movie Station |accessdate=6 March 2011|quote=Filming Locations: Croxteth Hall, Croxteth, Liverpool, Merseyside, England, UK ... Isle of Man ... Liverpool, Merseyside, England, UK}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/AVF159003 |title= The tichborne claimant |publisher=British Board of Film Classification |date= 23 November 2000 |accessdate=14 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nYates returned to television in 2000 to direct the episodes of ''Greed'', ''Envy'' and ''Lust'' for the BBC miniseries ''[[The Sins]]'', starring [[Pete Postlethwaite]], as well as ''[[The Way We Live Now (2001 TV serial)|The Way We Live Now]]'', the four-part television adaptation of the [[The Way We Live Now|novel of the same name]] by [[Anthony Trollope]]. Yates shared the [[British Academy Television Awards#Categories|British Academy Television Award for Best Drama Serial]] with screenwriter [[Andrew Davies (writer)|Andrew Davies]] and producer [[Nigel Stafford-Clark]] at the [[British Academy Television Awards 2002|2002 BAFTA Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/nominations/?year=2002 |title=Past Winners and Nominees \u2013 Film \u2013 Awards \u2013 the BAFTA site, Film Nominations 2002 |publisher=British Academy of Film and Television Arts|accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nOne year later, Yates attended the [[56th British Academy Film Awards|56th BAFTA Awards]] with a [[BAFTA Award for Best Short Film|British Academy Film Award nomination for Best Short Film]] for the fourteen-minute production, ''[[Rank (film)|Rank]]'', which expressed the social elements of racism, friendship and adolescence through the story of a street gang that cross [[Glasgow]] to witness the arrival of a group of Somali refugees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.britfilms.com/britishfilms/catalogue/browse/?id=D9CC70591925b1964DGtH218B43F |title=The British Films Catalogue, Rank |publisher=Brit Films |accessdate=4 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061112235614/http://www.britfilms.com/britishfilms/catalogue/browse/?id=D9CC70591925b1964DGtH218B43F |archivedate=12 November 2006 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.film4.com/features/article/funding-your-short-film |title=Funding Your Short Film |publisher=Film4 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107032057/http://www.film4.com/features/article/funding-your-short-film |archivedate=7 November 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Yates said that even though ''The Way We Live Now'' was \"a very big production\" and \"enormous fun to do\", ''Rank'' was an opportunity to \"shake all that off\" and \"get back to [his] roots\". Of the casting, Yates said that he \"wanted to use non-actors to tell the story, to create a reality ... the kids we cast in Glasgow had never done a film before.\"<ref name=\"FilmLondon-DavidYates\"/> The film was noted for its gritty style and cinematography, with a review from ''Eye For Film'' stating that \"such intelligent use of camera and cast lifts Yates out of the pool of promising young directors into the front line of genuine hopefuls. This work demands respect.\"<ref name=\"NFTS-DavidYatesCourses\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eyeforfilm.co.uk/reviews.php?id=2278|title=Rank ... 4.5/5 stars|work=Angus Wolfe Murray, Eye for Film|accessdate=1 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe 2003 six-part thriller ''[[State of Play (TV serial)|State of Play]]'' was Yates's next achievement.<ref name=\"DavidYatesDoesItAll\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.moviemaker.com/directing/article/david_yates_harry_potter_and_the_half_blood_prince_20090708/ |title=David Yates Does It All |publisher=MovieMaker |date=9 July 2009 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130111074704/http://www.moviemaker.com/directing/article/david_yates_harry_potter_and_the_half_blood_prince_20090708/ |archivedate=11 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Yates collected the TV Spielfilm Award at the [[Cologne Conference]] in Germany and won the [[Directors Guild of Great Britain|Directors Guild of Great Britain Award]] for Outstanding Directorial Achievement.<ref name=\"DGA-DavidYatesDirectorProfile\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cologne-conference.de/en/meta/archive/2004/awardees  |title=TV Spielfilm Award 2004 \"State of Play\" by David Yates |publisher=Cologne Conference |accessdate=9 March 2011 |quote= This year's TV Spielfilm Award goes to David Yates' \"State of Play\". The Cologne Conference congratulates David Yates.}}</ref> The serial was recognised by various award ceremonies, receiving the [[Peabody Award]] for Broadcasting Excellence and being presented with two [[British Academy Television Craft Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/3720217.stm |title=State of Play wins craft Baftas |work=[[BBC]] |date=17 May 2004 |accessdate=1 August 2011}}</ref> The quality of the serial sparked Hollywood film bosses to consider [[State of Play (film)|adapting it into a film]], with producer [[Andrew Hauptman]] declaring that \"it's a blistering political thriller and we want to make an equally blistering movie.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4076367.stm  |title=Hollywood Calls for State of Play |work=BBC News   |date= 7 December 2004 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> ''State of Play'' is regarded by critics from ''[[The Guardian]]'' and ''[[The Times]]'' as one of the best British television dramas of the 2000s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.memorabletv.com/new/state-of-play.html |title=State of Play (BBC Drama series) DVD review |publisher=MemorableTV |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221054127/http://www.memorabletv.com/new/state-of-play.html |archivedate=21 February 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2010/jan/12/guardian-50-television-dramas  |title=The Guardian's top 50 television dramas of all time |work=The Guardian |location=London |author=Tim Lusher|date=12 January 2010|accessdate=7 March 2011|quote=Our TV critics have voted, debated and decided on a top 50 of classic TV drama series}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article6955835.ece  |title=The top 50 TV shows of the Noughties|work=The Times |location=UK |publisher=Andrew Billen, David Chater, Tim Teeman, Caitlin Moran.|date=19 December 2009|accessdate=7 March 2011|quote=Fists fly as The Times's frontline TV critics argue out the best 50 programmes of the decade |first=Greg |last=Hurst}}</ref>\n\nYates directed the television adaptation of nine-year-old [[Daisy Ashford]]'s novel ''[[The Young Visiters#Adaptations|The Young Visiters]]'', starring [[Jim Broadbent]] alongside [[Hugh Laurie]]. According to a review by [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']] magazine for [[BBC America]], Yates and his team yielded \"a warm and surprisingly unsentimental production that has 'evergreen' written all over it\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117925407?refCatId=32  |title=The Young Visiters (Movie \u2013 BBC America; Wednesday, Nov.&nbsp;3, 8 p.m.) |work=Variety   |date= 31 October 2004 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |first=Brian |last=Lowry}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Yates's two-part drama ''[[Sex Traffic]]'' was broadcast on [[Channel 4]]. It won eight BAFTA Awards including [[BAFTA Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]] for [[Mark Day (editor)|Mark Day]], who regularly worked with Yates on many of his television projects and short films. Day commented on his collaboration with Yates saying that \"we are very good friends because we have spent so much time together\". He also said, \"David shoots in a similar style from piece to piece, although this wasn\u2019t quite as frantic as ''State of Play''.\"<ref name=\"EditorWinsBAFTA\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/s/52439_editor_wins_his_second_consecutive_bafta_award_over_campaigning_drama  |title=Editor wins his second consecutive BAFTA award over campaigning drama |publisher=Get Surrey |date= 19 May 2005 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> Yates was nominated for another Directors Guild of Great Britain Award for his direction of ''Sex Traffic'' and won his second BAFTA for Best Drama Serial at the British Academy Television Awards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bafta.org/awards-database.html?year=2004&category=Television&award=Drama+Serial  |title=Awards Database \u2013 The BAFTA site |publisher=BAFTA (bafta.org) |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> Being a British-Canadian production, ''Sex Traffic'' gained four wins at Canada's annual television award ceremony, the [[Gemini Award]]s, including Best Dramatic Mini-Series. Spanning across two parts, the three-hour-long drama reveals how the [[Human trafficking|trafficking of young women]] into slavery is a big business which operates throughout Europe; both parts were acclaimed for their \"shocking\" portrayal of such a sensitive topic.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/AVV227775  |title=BBFC ... Sex Traffic |publisher=British Board of Film Classification |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/1277745/ |title=BFI ScreenOnline: Sex Traffic (2004) |author=Neil Sinyard |publisher=BFI ScreenOnline |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ifcfilms.com/films/sex-traffic |title=About Sex Traffic |work=IFC Films |accessdate=4 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707113746/http://www.ifcfilms.com/films/sex-traffic |archivedate=7 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2004, Yates was involved in plans for a film adaptation of [[Evelyn Waugh]]'s novel ''[[Brideshead Revisited]]'' for [[Warner Independent Pictures]]. He was set to work with [[Paul Bettany]], [[Jude Law]] and [[Jennifer Connelly]] on the project, but pulled out in the later stages due to constant budget issues affecting the film's production.<ref name=\"DarkHorizons-DavidYatesBridesheadRevisited&HBP\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.darkhorizons.com/features/1448/david-yates-for-harry-potter-and-the-half-blood-prince  |title=Exclusive Interview: David Yates for \"Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince\" |publisher=Paul Fischer, Dark Horizons |date= 13 July 2009 |accessdate=4 March 2011| quote=He had been developing a version of Evelyn Waugh's novel, Brideshead Revisited in 2004 for the studio's art house division, Warner Independent Pictures, with husband-and-wife actors Paul Bettany and Jennifer Connolly negotiating to play the leads, but after finally landing the highly coveted \"Potter\" job and with budget issues stalling \"Brideshead,\" Yates transitioned into his new assignment.}}</ref><ref name=\"VarietyReviewsBrideshead\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117937762?refcatid=31  |title=Variety Reviews: Brideshead Revisited |work=Variety   |date=18 July 2008 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |quote=Reportedly, Paul Bettany, Jude Law and Jennifer Connelly were attached until helmer David Yates was poached for last year's \"Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix.\" One can say, in this case, that settling for the B team turned out well. |first=Dennis |last=Harvey}}</ref>\n\nYates then directed [[Richard Curtis]]' script to ''[[The Girl in the Caf\u00e9]]'', a television film starring [[Bill Nighy]] and [[Kelly Macdonald]]. In June 2005, the film was aired on the BBC in Britain and was also broadcast in the United States on [[HBO|Home Box Office]]. ''The Girl in the Caf\u00e9'' achieved three wins at the [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]s, including the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Made for Television Movie]], and gained a total of four nominations including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Miniseries, Movie or a Dramatic Special|Outstanding Directing]] for Yates.<ref name=\"Yahoo!Movies-DavidYatesBio\"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://movies.msn.com/celebrities/celebrity-awards-and-nominations/david-yates.1/ |title=David Yates \u2013 Awards & Nominations (Emmy Award) |publisher=MSN Movies |accessdate=4 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119021642/http://movies.msn.com/celebrities/celebrity-awards-and-nominations/david-yates.1/ |archive-date=19 January 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000223/2006  |title=Emmy Awards for 2006 |website=IMDb  |date= 19 August 2006 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n===''Harry Potter'' (2006\u20132011)===\n[[File:David Yates.jpg|thumb|left|Yates outside [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] at the premiere of ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]'' on 8 July 2007]]\nDuring the period of working on plans for ''Brideshead Revisited'', Yates was told by his agent that he had made the director shortlist for the fifth film in the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' series]]. He was then confirmed to direct ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]'' by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]], with production scheduled to begin in early 2006.<ref name=\"VarietyReviewsBrideshead\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hpana.com/news.18428.html  |title=David Yates confirms 'Order of the Phoenix' role |publisher=HPANA (source: This is Wiltshire) |date=29 November 2004 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> When asked how Yates got the job, producer [[David Heyman]] (\"a big fan\" of Yates's television work)<ref name=\"TheObserver-DavidYatesinterview\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2007/jun/24/harrypotter  |title=How I raised Potter's bar |work=The Observer |location=London |author=Amy Raphael |date=24 June 2007 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |quote= Without wishing to sound rude, how did he get the job? 'You're not the first to ask,' he laughs...}}</ref> said that \"actors in David's television projects give their best performance, often of their career. It's important to keep pushing the actors, particularly the young ones on each ''Potter'' film. This is a political film, not with a capital P, but it's about teen rebellion and the abuse of power. David has made films in the U.K. about politics without being heavy handed.\"<ref name=\"HeymanYatesOOTP\">{{cite news |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117968266?refcatid=1288 |title=WB Wild For Harry Potter |work=Variety |date=9 July 2007 |accessdate=15 June 2011 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro}}</ref>\n\nBefore production began, Yates invited ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]'' director [[Mike Newell (director)|Mike Newell]] to a pub and \"picked his brains about what it was going to be like to step into someone's shoes on a movie of this scale\".<ref name=\"DGA-DavidYatesDirectorProfile\"/> The first scene that Yates shot featured a [[Giant (mythology)|giant]] interacting with human characters. The scene was the very first high-scale [[visual effects]] piece Yates filmed in his career.<ref name=\"DGA-DavidYatesDirectorProfile\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2010/exclusive-interview-harry-potter-series-producer-david-heyman/  |title=Exclusive Interview: 'Harry Potter' Producer David Heyman |author=Alex Billington |publisher=FirstShowing.net |date=9 December 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> After the film's post-production material was well received by the studio, Yates was chosen to direct the sixth film, ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'', which according to Yates was going to be \"a cross between the chills of ''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (film)|Prisoner of Azkaban]]'' [the third film in the series] and the fantastical adventure of ''Goblet of Fire''\".<ref name=\"VirginMedia-DavidYates\"/><ref name=\"DarkHorizons-DavidYatesBridesheadRevisited&HBP\"/>\n\nIn 2007, ''Order of the Phoenix'' opened to positive reviews and commercial success. Yates won the title of [[Empire Award for Best Director|Best Director]] at the [[Empire Awards]] and collected the [[European Film Academy People's Choice Award for Best European Film|People's Choice Award]] from the [[European Film Academy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.europeanfilmacademy.org/The-Peoples-Choice-Awards-Winners.60.0.html |title=European Film Awards, 2008 |publisher=European Film Academy |date= 6 December 2008 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> However, the film was criticised by fans of the series for having the shortest running time out of the five released instalments; Yates said that the original director's cut was \"probably over three hours\", resulting in much footage being cut, condensed and edited to fit within the studio's preferred time frame.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2006/10/27/ootp-director-david-yates-i-ve-shot-a-movie-that-s-probably-over-three-hours |title=OotP Director David Yates: \"I've Shot a Movie That's Probably Over Three Hours\" |author=Sue Upton |publisher=The Leaky Cauldron |work=Empire Magazine |date= 27 October 2006 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/harry-potter-and-the-order-of-phoenix-shortened-to-avoid-grindhouse-failure/ |title=Harry Potter and The Order of Phoenix Shortened to Avoid Grindhouse Failure? |author=Peter Sciretta |publisher=SlashFilm |date= 13 April 2007 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring production of ''Half-Blood Prince'', Warner Bros. executive [[Alan F. Horn]] announced that the seventh and final novel in the series, ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]'', was to be split into two cinematic parts with Yates, once again, as the director.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/movies/la-et-potter13mar13,0,7162166.story |title=Final 'Harry Potter' book will be split into two movies |author=Geoff Boucher |work=Los Angeles Times |date= 13 March 2008 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> Yates spoke of the decision to appoint him as the director of the final films, remarking that \"they wanted to do a ''Harry Potter'' that felt ... more grown up. What's smart about the studio and the producers is they have always wanted to push it a bit. [[Chris Columbus (filmmaker)|Chris Columbus]] did a wonderful job of casting and making this world incredibly popular. But rather than do more of the same, they said, 'Let's bring in [[Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n]] and let him run with it. Then later, let's bring in David Yates, who's done all this hard-hitting stuff on TV.' It's a testament to their ambition to try to keep the franchise fresh. The bizarre thing is, I did one [film] and they asked me to stay for three more, so obviously they liked something.\"<ref name=\"DGA-DavidYatesDirectorProfile\"/>\n\n''Half-Blood Prince'' was released in 2009 and became the only film in the series to earn an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/harry_potter_and_the_half_blood_prince/news/1831803/tomatometer_watch_how_good_is_harry_potter_and_the_half_blood_prince |title=Tomatometer Watch: How Good is Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince? |publisher=Jen Yamato, Rotten Tomatoes |date= 10 July 2009 |accessdate=6 March 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/2009-academy-award-nominations-announced/ |title=82nd Annual Academy Award Nominations Announced |author=Russ Fischer |publisher=Slash Film |date=2 February 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2011 }}</ref> Yates worked alongside French cinematographer [[Bruno Delbonnel]] on, what Yates called, extensively colour grading the \"incredibly rich\" picture by making it look \"very European\" and drawing influences from the Dutch painter [[Rembrandt]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/harry-potter-and-the-half-blood-prince-3/page:3 |title=Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince ... We go on set for the latest Potter picture |magazine=Total Film |date=1 April 2009|accessdate=7 March 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Film-Review/harry-potter-the-half-blood-prince-david-yates-interview |title=Harry Potter & The Half-Blood Prince \u2013 David Yates interview |publisher=IndieLondon |accessdate=6 March 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/112/1125648p1.html |title=Harry Potter: The Journey Ends Here |author=Orlando Parfitt |publisher=IGN Movies |date=5 October 2010 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713004816/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/112/1125648p1.html |archivedate=13 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The film garnered a mix of accolades and was acclaimed for its stylised character-driven approach, but some fans complained about the script's deviation from the novel and the film's slight [[romantic comedy]] nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/harry_potter_and_the_half_blood_prince/news/1832250/rt_interview_david_yates_on_harry_potter_and_the_half_blood_prince |title=RT Interview: David Yates on Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince |author=Joe Utichi |website=Rotten Tomatoes |date=15 July 2009 |accessdate=6 March 2011 |quote=Includes fan comments}}</ref> In response to this criticism, renowned BAFTA member and film critic [[Mark Kermode]] praised Yates's direction and ranked the film \"second best\" in the series, behind ''Prisoner of Azkaban''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02n9kzh |title=Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince reviewed by Mark Kermode |publisher=BBC Radio 5 Live |date=16 November 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2011 |quote=This is the second best Harry Potter film.}}</ref>\n\nYates [[Production of Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows|began to film]] ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1|Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1]]'' and ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2|Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2]]'' back-to-back in early 2009 and finished reshoots in late 2010.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://filmonic.com/deathly-hallows-epilogue-scenes-to-be-reshot-over-christmas |title=Deathly Hallows epilogue scenes to be reshot over Christmas |work=Filmonic |date=13 November 2010 |accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> He stated that he had shot the two parts of the final adaptation differently, with Part 1 being a \"[[road movie]]\" and \"quite real\", \"almost like a [[Cin\u00e9ma v\u00e9rit\u00e9|v\u00e9rit\u00e9]] documentary\", while Part 2 is \"more operatic, colourful and [[fantasy film|fantasy-oriented]]\", a \"big opera with huge battles.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nationalpost.com/todays-paper/Harry+Potter+last+goodbye/3848043/story.html |title=Harry Potter & the last goodbye |publisher=Bob Thompson, Postmedia News |date=18 November 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2011 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.filmschoolrejects.com/news/if-the-harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-two-film-adaptation-were-a-person-this-splitting-point-would-be-the-taint.php |title=If The Two Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows Films Were A Person This Would Be The Perineum |publisher=Rob Hunter, Film School Rejects |date=13 August 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623214612/http://www.filmschoolrejects.com/news/if-the-harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-two-film-adaptation-were-a-person-this-splitting-point-would-be-the-taint.php |archivedate=23 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2010/1/24/david-yates-deathly-hallows-a-big-opera-a-great-big-epic-with-huge-battles |title=David Yates: \"Deathly Hallows\" a \"big opera, a great big epic, with huge battles\" |publisher=Edward, The Leaky Cauldron (source: Total Film Magazine)|date=24 January 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> Yates reshot the final scene of the ''Harry Potter'' series at [[Warner Bros. Studios, Leavesden|Leavesden Studios]] after the original version, filmed at [[London King's Cross railway station]], did not meet his expectations. In the film, the scene takes place at the magical [[Platform 9\u00be]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://screenrant.com/harry-potter-deathly-hallows-epilogue-sirius-scorpius-actors-benk-93896/ |title=Harry Potter's 'Deathly Hallows' Epilogue Reshoot Complete; Adds 'Severus' Child-Actor |work=Ben Kendrick at Screenrant |date=December 2010 |accessdate=9 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nPart 1 was released worldwide in November 2010 to commercial success along with generally positive reviews, some of which reflected on Yates's directing style. ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' affirmed that \"David Yates' fluid, fast-paced direction sends up the crackling tension of a thriller\" and ''[[The New York Times]]'' analysed Yates's approach to J. K. Rowling's character development by saying that he has \"demonstrated a thorough, uncondescending sympathy for her characters, in particular the central trio of [[Ron Weasley]], [[Hermione Granger]] and [[Harry Potter (character)|Harry Potter]] himself.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.casarotto.co.uk/news/david-yates-harry-potter-breaks-box-office-records-12330 |title=David Yates' Harry Potter breaks Box Office records |publisher=Casarotto (source: BBC News) |date=23 November 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807145729/http://www.casarotto.co.uk/news/david-yates-harry-potter-breaks-box-office-records-12330 |archive-date=7 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2010/11/19/movies/19harry.html|title=Time for Young Wizards to Put Away Childish Things |author=A. O. Scott |work=The New York Times |date=18 November 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> The film was praised for its \"dark\" atmosphere and its loyalty to the source material, but it was criticised for its slow middle act, the handling of exposition, and the somewhat disjointed pacing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/harry_potter_and_the_deathly_hallows_part_i/ |title=Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows Part 1 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/71686,news-comment,entertainment,what-theyre-saying-about-harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-part-1|title=What they're saying about the new Harry Potter film |author=Natalie Davies |magazine=The First Post |date=20 November 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nPart 2 was screened in July 2011 and became an instant record-breaking success with critical acclaim.<ref name=\"DH2RT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/harry_potter_and_the_deathly_hallows_part_ii/ |title=Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part II (2011) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"DH2MC\">{{cite news| url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-part-2 |title=Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part 2 |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=15 July 2011}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' described Part 2 as \"monumental cinema awash with gorgeous tones\" and ''[[Total Film]]'' wrote that Yates combines \"spectacle and emotion into a thrilling final chapter.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/harry-potter/8619487/Harry-Potter-and-the-Deathly-Hallow-Part-2-review.html |title=Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows, Part 2, review |author=Philip Womack |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date= 6 July 2011 |accessdate=6 July 2011 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/reviews/cinema/harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-part-2?ns_campaign=reviews&ns_mchannel=rss&ns_source=totalfilm&ns_linkname=0&ns_fee=0 |title=Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part 2 |work=[[Total Film]] |date=7 July 2011 |accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref> Author J. K. Rowling remarked that \"everyone who watches ''Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2'' is going to see that he's steered us home magnificently. It's incredible.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.movies.yahoo.com/blog/article/221834/harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-part-2reviewed.html |title=Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part 2 \u2013 reviewed |work=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |date=8 July 2011 |accessdate=9 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711134618/http://uk.movies.yahoo.com/blog/article/221834/harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-part-2reviewed.html |archivedate=11 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/markkermode/2011/07/wild_about_harry.html |title=Wild About Harry |work=[[BBC]] |date=15 July 2011 |accessdate=16 July 2011}}</ref> Part 2 is the only ''Harry Potter'' film to pass the $1 billion mark during its original theatrical run; it became the [[List of highest-grossing films#Worldwide highest-grossing films|highest-grossing]] film in the series and the highest-grossing film of 2011, making Yates the director of the highest-grossing non-[[James Cameron]] film of all time in August 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110731005089/en/%E2%80%9CHarry-Potter-Deathly-Hallows-%E2%80%93-Part-2%E2%80%9D |title=\"Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2\" Crosses $1 Billion Threshold |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=31 July 2011 |accessdate=31 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/harry-potter-deathly-hallows-part-220419 |title='Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows Part 2' Becomes No. 3 Film of All Time at Box Office |work=Pamela McClintock, [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=8 August 2011 |accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> Amongst other accolades, Yates won his second Empire Award for Best Director and joined the principal creative team of ''Harry Potter'' in receiving the 2012 [[ADG Excellence in Production Design Award|ADG Award for Outstanding Contribution to Cinematic Imagery]] for their work on ''Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2'' and the series in general.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118045381 |title=ADG to fete 'Harry Potter' creative team |date=1 November 2011 |accessdate=14 December 2011 |work=Variety |first=Dave |last=McNary}}</ref>\n\nYates attended the [[64th British Academy Film Awards]] in February 2011, where he was joined by J. K. Rowling, David Heyman, Mike Newell, Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n, [[David Barron (film producer)|David Barron]], [[Rupert Grint]], and [[Emma Watson]] in collecting the [[64th British Academy Film Awards#Michael Balcon Award for Outstanding British Contribution to Cinema|Michael Balcon Award for Outstanding British Contribution to Cinema]] on behalf of the ''Harry Potter'' films. [[Daniel Radcliffe]], who portrayed the films' titular character, commented on working with Yates, saying that he \"added his own sense of grit and realism [to the series] that perhaps wasn't there so much before. I think we all had a fantastic time working with David. I know we did.\"<ref name=\"DavidYatesEarlyLifeBAFTA\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Film-Review/harry-potter-the-order-of-the-phoenix-daniel-radcliffe-interview |title=Daniel Radcliffe interview |publisher=IndieLondon |accessdate=9 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Subsequent work (2012\u2013present)===\nBy 2012, Yates was working on a few [[Warner Bros.]] projects, including a ''Tarzan'' feature film and an [[Al Capone]] biopic called ''Cicero''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.totalfilm.com/news/tom-hardy-attached-to-play-al-capone-in-a-david-yates-cicero |title=Tom Hardy attached to play Al Capone in a David Yates' Cicero |work=[[Total Film]] |accessdate=19 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2012/11/david-yates-committing-to-tarzan-at-warner-bros.html?MID=TWITTER_VULTURE|title=David Yates Committing to Tarzan at Warner Bros. -- Vulture|author=Claude Brodesser-Akner|work=Vulture}}</ref> He also controversially said that he was working with [[BBC Worldwide]] on plans to develop a ''[[Doctor Who]]'' film,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://collider.com/doctor-who-movie-david-yates/126358/ |title=David Yates to Direct DOCTOR WHO Movie |date=14 November 2011 |accessdate=15 November 2011}}</ref> although this was denied by the showrunner, [[Steven Moffat]], in July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/07/30/doctor-who-steven-moffat-2/|title='Doctor Who' film rumors 'a weird fantasy'|work=Entertainment Weekly's EW.com}}</ref> Because of production delays, Yates began to explore other projects including television work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/04/tarzan-dying-on-the-vine-at-warner-bros/|title='Tarzan' Dying On The Vine At Warner Bros? - Deadline|author=Mike Fleming Jr|work=Deadline}}</ref>\n\n[[File:David Yates (27996598333).jpg|thumb|right|Yates speaking at [[San Diego Comic-Con|San Diego Comic-Con International]], 2016]]\nIn 2013, he returned to television by signing on to direct the [[television pilot]] of ''[[Tyrant (TV series)|Tyrant]]'', an American drama production set against the US\u2013Middle East conflict.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/harry-potters-david-yates-direct-567654 | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Lacey | last=Rose | title=Harry Potter's' David Yates to Direct FX Drama Pilot 'Tyrant | date=12 June 2013}}</ref> The following year, Yates began shooting ''[[The Legend of Tarzan (film)|The Legend of Tarzan]]'', starring [[Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd]], [[Samuel L. Jackson]], [[Margot Robbie]], [[Djimon Hounsou]], [[Jim Broadbent]], and [[Christoph Waltz]]. The film, released in 2016, opened to mixed reviews and a worldwide total of $356.7 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=tarzan2016.htm |title=The Legend of Tarzan (2016) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nYates directed ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]'', a 2016 film which is the first in a series of five instalments based on J. K. Rowling's book, set in the world of her ''Harry Potter'' novels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hypable.com/2014/10/15/fantastic-beasts-director-david-yates/|title=WB names David Yates 'Fantastic Beasts' director|work=Hypable}}</ref> David Heyman and ''Harry Potter'' screenwriter [[Steve Kloves]] joined Yates and J. K. Rowling in developing the script.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.themarysue.com/heyman-fantastic-beasts-fables/|title = X-Men's Jane Goldman Joining Fables Film Writing Team, Updates on Rowling's Fantastic Beasts|date = 20 January 2015|accessdate = 20 January 2015|website = The Mary Sue}}</ref> The film was released in November 2016, it received generally positive reviews and was a commercial  success having grossed $814 million , The film stars [[Eddie Redmayne]], [[Katherine Waterston]], [[Dan Fogler]], [[Alison Sudol]], [[Ezra Miller]], [[Colin Farrell]], and [[Johnny Depp]]. Yates directed the 2018 sequel, ''[[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]'' which received mixed critical reception but emerged a box office success having grossed $654 million. In an interview with ''The Hollywood Reporter'', he stated he was open to directing all five planned films in the ''Fantastic Beasts'' series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/fantastic-beasts-david-yates-says-hes-directing-all-five-films-946671|title=David Yates Says He's Directing All Five 'Fantastic Beasts' Films|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2016-11-12}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYates has a younger brother and an elder sister.<ref name=\"DavidYatesCollider2011\"/> He is married to Yvonne Walcott.<ref name=Star>{{cite news |author=Simon Mulligan |url=https://www.sthelensstar.co.uk/news/15105128.harry-potter-director-david-yates-named-citizen-of-honour-at-liverpool-city-hall/ |title=Harry Potter director David Yates named Citizen of Honour at Liverpool City Hall |newspaper=St Helens Star |date=21 February 2017 |accessdate=28 June 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Directing style==\n[[Emma Watson]] stated that Yates liked to push the cast and crew to physical and emotional extremes, with [[Gary Oldman]] confirming Yates's preference for working slowly by shooting numerous [[take]]s to draw the best performances out of the cast.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a287844/emma-watson-cried-at-director-yates.html |title=Emma Watson 'cried at director Yates' |work=[[Digital Spy]] |date=15 November 2010 |accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.metro.co.uk/film/865710-gary-oldman-im-not-sad-about-the-end-of-harry-potter |title=Gary Oldman: I'm not sad about the end of Harry Potter| work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date= 8 June 2011 |accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> Yates has been influenced by such directors as [[Steven Spielberg]], [[David Lean]], and [[Ken Loach]].<ref name=\"FilmLondon-DavidYates\">{{Cite news|url=http://filmlondon.org.uk/news/2007/december/david_yates_on_harry_potter |title=David Yates on Harry Potter|publisher=Film London |date=23 December 2007 |accessdate=11 March 2011}}</ref> Yates's style of work includes social and political themes, character-driven narratives, realism, and atmospheric drama.<ref name=\"DavidYatesBaltimore2\">{{cite news |url=http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/movies/blog/2011/06/brush_up_on_harry_potter_at_ho.html |title=Brush up on Harry Potter at Hopkins and Lakefront Film Festivals |work=Baltimore Sun |date= 10 June 2011|accessdate=14 June 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emanuellevy.com/comment/harry-potters-new-director-david-yates-6/ |title=Harry Potter's New Director David Yates |work=Emanuel Levy (cinema 24/7) |accessdate=21 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322054822/http://www.emanuellevy.com/comment/harry-potters-new-director-david-yates-6/ |archive-date=22 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"David Yates RTV\">{{cite news |url=http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20090710/david-yates-director-que-pone-punto-final-saga-harry-potter/284476.shtml |title=David Yates, the director who puts an end to saga of 'Harry Potter' |work=RTV.es |date=10 July 2009 |accessdate=21 June 2011 |quote= His work is defined by the use of political and social elements ... expertise to address specific issues such as corruption...}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n=== Feature films ===\n* ''[[The Tichborne Claimant (film)|The Tichborne Claimant]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[The Legend of Tarzan (film)|The Legend of Tarzan]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]'' (2018)\n* ''Fantastic Beasts 3'' (2021)\n* ''Fantastic Beasts 4'' (TBA)\n* ''Fantastic Beasts 5'' (TBA)\n\n=== Short films ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Director\n![[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n!Producer\n|-\n|1988\n|''When I Was a Girl''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1991\n|''The Weaver's Wife''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|-\n|''Oranges and Lemons''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n|-\n|1992\n|''Good Looks''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n|-\n|1996\n|''Punch''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Rank (film)|Rank]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Director\n!Producer\n!Episode(s)\n!Notes\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Moving Pictures (TV series)|Moving Pictures]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|<nowiki>''Low Budget''</nowiki>\n| TV Series documentary\n|-\n|1994-95\n|''[[The Bill]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|<nowiki>''Death and Taxes'', ''Full Contact'', ''Life's a Bitch''</nowiki>, <nowiki>''Feeling Guilty'', ''Other Voice''</nowiki>\n|TV Series\n|-\n|1995\n| ''Tale of Three Seaside Towns''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|All 3 episodes <small>(co-directing with Alistair Clarke)</small>\n| TV Series documentary\n|-\n| 2000\n|''[[The Sins]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|<nowiki>''</nowiki>Lust<nowiki>''</nowiki>, <nowiki>''</nowiki>Envy<nowiki>''</nowiki>, <nowiki>''</nowiki>Greed<nowiki>''</nowiki>\n| TV Mini-Series\n|-\n| 2001\n|''[[The Way We Live Now (2001 TV serial)|The Way We Live Now]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|All 4 episodes\n|TV Mini-Series\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2003\n|''[[State of Play (TV serial)|State of Play]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|All 6 episodes\n|TV Mini-Series\n|-\n|''[[The Young Visiters]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 2004\n|''[[Sex Traffic]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|All 2 episodes\n| TV Mini-Series\n|-\n| 2005\n|''[[The Girl in the Caf\u00e9]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|{{n/a}}\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 2014\n|''[[Tyrant (TV series)|Tyrant]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes|Executive}}\n|<nowiki>''Pilot''</nowiki>\n| TV Series\n|-\n|}\n\n==Accolades==\n''Only certain awards for Yates's direction are shown in this section. A complete list of awards for a project may be found on its article page.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Award \n! Category\n! Title\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1991\n| [[Cork Film Festival|Cork International Film Festival]]\n| Best European Short\n| ''When I Was a Girl''\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[San Francisco International Film Festival]]:<br />[[San Francisco International Film Festival#Golden Gate Awards|Golden Gate Award]]<br />\n| Best Short Film\n| ''When I Was a Girl''\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Belfort Film Festival\n| Best Film\n| ''When I Was a Girl''\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| 1992\n| [[Chicago International Film Festival]]: Silver Hugo\n| \u2013\n| ''Good Looks''\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| 1998\n| Emden Film Festival Award\n| \u2013\n| ''The Tichborne Claimant''\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2002\n| [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]]: [[British Academy Television Awards|British Academy Television Award]]\n| Best Drama Serial\n| ''The Way We Live Now''\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2003\n| [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]]: [[British Academy Film Awards|British Academy Film Award]]\n| Best Short Film\n| ''Rank''\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Directors Guild of Great Britain]]\n| Outstanding Directorial Achievement in a TV Movie/Serial\n| ''State of Play''\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2004\n| [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]]: [[British Academy Television Awards|British Academy Television Award]]\n| Best Drama Serial\n| ''State of Play''\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Cologne Conference|Cologne Conference: TV Spielfilm Award]]\n| Best Fiction Programme\n| ''State of Play''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Directors Guild of Great Britain]]\n| Outstanding Directorial Achievement in a TV Movie/Mini-Series\n| ''Sex Traffic''\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2005\n| [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]]: [[British Academy Television Awards|British Academy Television Award]]\n| Best Drama Serial\n| ''Sex Traffic''\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Prix Italia]]\n| Best TV Movie or Mini-Series\n| ''Sex Traffic''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2006\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award]]\n| Outstanding Directing for a Mini-Series, Movie or Dramatic Special\n| ''The Girl in the Caf\u00e9''\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2008\n| [[Empire Awards|Empire Award]]\n| Best Director\n| ''Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix''\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award]]\n| Best Director\n| ''Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix''\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20121020113653/http://nftsfilm-tv.ac.uk/who-we-are/honorary-fellows NFTS Honorary Fellowship]\n| Outstanding Contribution to the British Film and Television Industry\n| \u2013\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2011\n| [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]]: [[Britannia Awards|Britannia Award (Los Angeles)]]\n| John Schlesinger Britannia Award for Excellence in Directing\n| ''Harry Potter''<br />{{small|''Order of the Phoenix'', ''Half-Blood Prince'', ''Deathly Hallows''}}\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award]]\n| Best Director\n| ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[2011 Scream Awards|Scream Award]]\n| Best Director\n| ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2''\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2012\n| [[Saturn Award]]\n| Best Director\n| ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[SFX (magazine)|SFX Award]]\n| Best Director\n| ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Empire Awards|Empire Award]]\n| Best Director\n| ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[University of Essex]]\n| Honorary Degree\n| \u2013\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|2016\n|| [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]]: [[British Academy Film Awards|British Academy Film Award]]\n|Outstanding British Film\n|''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Reception==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Film\n! [[Rotten Tomatoes]]<ref>{{cite web | title=David Yates | url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/celebrity/david_yates | website=Rotten Tomatoes | accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n! [[Metacritic]]<ref>{{cite web | title=David Yates |url=https://www.metacritic.com/person/david-yates | website=Metacritic |accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref>\n! [[CinemaScore]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cinemascore.com/ | title=CinemaScore | work=cinemascore.com | accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref>\n! Budget\n! Box office<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=davidyates.htm | title=David Yates Movie Box office | work=boxofficemojo.com | accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix'' || 78% (249 reviews)<br>{{small|(6.9/10)}} || 71 (37 reviews) || A\u2013 || $150 million || $940 million\n|-\n| ''Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince'' || 83% (272 reviews)<br>{{small|(7.12/10)}} || 78 (36 reviews) || A\u2013 || $250 million || $934.4 million\n|-\n| ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1'' || 77% (273 reviews)<br>{{small|(7.13/10)}} || 65 (42 reviews) || A || rowspan=\"2\"| $250 million || $960.3 million\n|-\n| ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2'' || 96% (323 reviews)<br>{{small|(8.33/10)}} || 87 (41 reviews) || A || $1.342 billion\n|-\n| ''The Legend of Tarzan'' || 36% (241 reviews)<br>{{small|(5.07/10)}} || 44 (41 reviews) || A\u2013 || $180 million || $356.7 million \n|-\n| ''Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them'' || 74% (317 reviews)<br>{{small|(6.84/10)}} || 66 (50 reviews) || A || $180 million || $814 million\n|-\n| ''Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald'' || 37% (298 reviews)<br>{{small|(5.29/10)}} || 52 (48 reviews) || B+ || $200 million || $654.9 million\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|David Yates}}\n*{{IMDb name|0946734}}\n*[http://www.bafta.org/losangeles/news/david-yates,1905,BA.html David Yates: British Academy of Film and Television Arts]\n*[http://www.dga.org/The-Guild/Members/Profile.aspx?mid=fk1mYpRzTf4%3d David Yates: Directors Guild of America]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|before=[[Mike Newell (director)|Mike Newell]]|title=[[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'']] film director|years=[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|2007]]\u2013[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2|2011]]|after=End of Series}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|before=[[Alan Parker]]|title=[[National Film and Television School|NFTS]] Honorary Fellowship|years=2010|after=[[Jonathan Ross]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{David Yates}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for David Yates\n|list =\n{{Empire Award for Best Director}}\n{{BAFTA Los Angeles Britannia Awards}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yates, David}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Essex]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:Best Director Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:English film directors]]\n[[Category:English television directors]]\n[[Category:People from St Helens, Merseyside]]\n[[Category:Fantasy film directors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the National Film and Television School]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix=\n| name            = David Yates\n| image           = David Yates by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| imagesize       =\n| caption         = Yates at the 2016 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1963|10|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]],<ref name=\"DavidYatesEarlyLifeBAFTA\"/> [[Lancashire]]<!-- St Helens was part of Lancashire in 1963, please do not change to Merseyside -->, England\n| alma_mater      = [[University of Essex]]\n| notable_works   = [[Wizarding World|''Wizarding World'' franchise]]\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| occupation      = Filmmaker\n| years_active    = 1988\u2013present\n| spouse          = Yvonne Walcott\n| awards          = \n}}\n'''David Yates''' (born {{birth date|1963|10|08|df=y}}) is an English [[Filmmaking|filmmaker]] who has directed films, short films, and television productions.\n\nYates directed the final four films in the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' series]].<ref name=\"DGA-DavidYatesDirectorProfile\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dga.org/Craft/DGAQ/All-Articles/1001-Spring-2010/Profile-David-Yates.aspx |title=The Wizard Behind the Camera |author=Andrew Pulver |publisher=DGA Quarterly, Directors Guild of America |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"BAFTABritannia\">{{cite news|url=http://losangeles.broadwayworld.com/article/BAFTA-Honors-John-Lasseter-and-David-Yates-1130-20110628 |title=BAFTA Honors John Lasseter and David Yates 11/30 |publisher=Broadway World (Los Angeles) |date=28 June 2011 |accessdate=28 June 2011 |quote=The worldwide success of Mr. Lasseter for Walt Disney and Pixar Animation Studios and Mr. Yates's contribution to the final four parts of the \u2018Harry Potter' franchise makes them global wizards in their own right, and are delighted to honor these remarkable filmmakers with this year's Britannia Award.}}</ref> His work on the series brought him critical and commercial success along with accolades, such as the [[Britannia Awards|British Academy Britannia Award for Excellence in Directing]].<ref name=\"BAFTABritannia\"/> Yates's subsequent projects include<!-- Only list the project name and its release date. Do not add any more awards. --> ''[[The Legend of Tarzan (film)|The Legend of Tarzan]]'' and ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]'' (both 2016), and its sequel, ''[[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]'' (2018).\n\nEarly in his career, Yates directed various short films and became a television director. His credits include the six-part political thriller ''[[State of Play (TV serial)|State of Play]]'' (2003), for which he won the [[Directors Guild of Great Britain|Directors Guild of Great Britain Award for Outstanding Directorial Achievement]], the adult two-part documentary drama ''[[Sex Traffic]]'' (2004) and the [[Emmy Award]]-winning television film ''[[The Girl in the Caf\u00e9]]'' (2005).<ref name=\"DGA-DavidYatesDirectorProfile\"/><ref name=\"DavidYatesDoesItAll\"/><ref name=\"VirginMedia-DavidYates\">{{cite news|url=http://www.virginmedia.com/movies/movieextras/top10s/potter-hbp-rumours.php |title=Ten Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince facts |publisher=Virgin Media |accessdate=19 April 2011|quote=Director David Yates, one of British TV's most respected director (thanks to the drama series State Of Play)...}}</ref>\n\nYates is a founding member of [[Directors UK]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/inside-story-in-the-right-direction--the-cream-of-britains-television-directing-talent-848048.html |title=Inside Story: In the right direction \u2013 the cream of Britain's television directing talent |work=[[The Independent]] |date=16 June 2008 |accessdate=3 August 2011 |location=London}}</ref> He has had a close partnership with [[Warner Bros.]] as a director and producer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118053263.html |title=David Yates inks first-look deal with Warner Bros. |work=Variety.com |date=27 April 2012 |accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDavid Yates was born in 1963 in Lancashire, England.{{#tag:ref|Yates was born in Lancashire, 1963, and was raised in the village of Rainhill. This was before the creation of the [[Metropolitan Borough of St Helens]], [[Merseyside]] in April 1974, in which Rainhill is now included.|group=\"n\"}} His parents died when he was young.<ref name=\"DavidYatesCollider2011\">{{cite news| url=https://collider.com/david-yates-interview-harry-potter-deathly-hallows-part-2/101507/?replytocom=155909#respond |title=Exclusive: Director David Yates Talks HARRY POTTER AND THE DEATHLY HALLOWS \u2013 PART 2, Deleted Scenes, Future Projects, and More |work=Collider.com |date=10 July 2011 |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> Raised in the village of [[Rainhill]], Yates was inspired to pursue a career in filmmaking after watching [[Steven Spielberg]]'s 1975 movie ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]''.<ref name=\"DavidYatesEarlyLifeBAFTA\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sthelensstar.co.uk/news/8850608.Yates_enjoys_Harry_Potter_BAFTA_honour/ |title=St Helens-born David Yates enjoys Harry Potter BAFTA honour |work=St Helens Star |date= 13 February 2011|accessdate=11 March 2011}}</ref> Yates's mother bought him a [[Super 8 film cameras|Super 8mm camera]]. He used this to shoot various films  in which his friends and family featured.<ref name=\"FilmLondon-DavidYates\"/> One such film, ''The Ghost Ship'', was shot on board the vessel where his uncle worked as a cook.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-life-features/liverpool-arts/2011/07/08/st-helen-s-born-director-david-yates-on-harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-part-2-92534-29014685/#ixzz1RapYxSNT |title=St Helens-born director David Yates on Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2 |author= Laura Davis|work=Liverpool Daily Post |date=8 July 2011 |accessdate=9 July 2011}}</ref> He attended Grange Park High School,<ref name=Star/> [[St Helens College]] and then the [[University of Essex]].<ref name=\"Yahoo!Movies-DavidYatesBio\">{{Cite news|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1807432789/bio |title=David Yates Biography |publisher=Yahoo! Movies |accessdate=4 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622012522/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1807432789/bio |archivedate=22 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sthelensreporter.co.uk/news/local/harry_potter_director_celebrates_box_office_smash_1_734230 |title=Harry Potter director celebrates box office smash |work=St Helens Reporter |date=3 August 2009 |accessdate=11 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"David Yates Casarotto\">{{cite news|url=http://www.casarotto.co.uk/assets/x/51023.pdf |title=David Yates |accessdate=16 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807145401/http://www.casarotto.co.uk/assets/x/51023.pdf |archivedate=7 August 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Yates said that he \"used to skive off college all the time\" and never expected to join university before being surprised by his A-Level exam results. While at the University of Essex, Yates formed the Film and Video Production Society.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/echofeatures/9835286.Directing_Harry_Potter_was_magic/ |title=Directing Harry Potter was Magic |work=Echo News |date=26 July 2012 |accessdate=23 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727123019/http://www.echo-news.co.uk/echofeatures/9835286.Directing_Harry_Potter_was_magic/ |archivedate=27 July 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> He graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in Government in 1987.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/event.aspx?e_id=4262 |title=Harry Potter director and Arctic explorer honoured at Graduation 2012 |work=University of Essex |date=17 July 2012 |accessdate=23 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130125213452/http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/event.aspx?e_id=4262 |archivedate=25 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Television and film career (1988\u20132005)===\n[[File:BeaconsfieldFilmStudios.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The [[National Film and Television School]], where Yates trained as a director<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nftsfilm-tv.ac.uk/who-we-are/honorary-fellows |title=Honorary Fellows |work=NFTS |accessdate=16 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020113653/http://nftsfilm-tv.ac.uk/who-we-are/honorary-fellows |archive-date=20 October 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>]]\n\nIn 1988, Yates made his first film ''When I Was a Girl'' in [[Swindon]]. The film entered the festival circuit where it was named [[San Francisco International Film Festival#Golden Gate Awards|Best Short Film]] at the [[San Francisco International Film Festival]]. It contributed towards Yates's acceptance into the [[National Film and Television School]] in 1989 and led to the [[BBC]] hiring him to direct ''Oranges and Lemons'', a short drama film in 1991. Before completing film school, he began to direct, produce and write the screenplay to the dramatic short ''The Weaver's Wife''. He also made his fourth short film, ''Good Looks'', which was presented at the [[Chicago International Film Festival]]. After graduating in 1992, Yates directed an episode of the film studies programme ''[[Moving Pictures (TV series)|Moving Pictures]]''.<ref name=\"FilmLondon-DavidYates\"/><ref name=\"Yahoo!Movies-DavidYatesBio\"/><ref name=\"NFTS-DavidYatesCourses\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nftsfilm-tv.ac.uk/index.php?module=People&type=Alumni&people_id=310&back=course&course_id=149 |title=Courses ... David Yates |work=nfts.co.uk |publisher=National Film and Television School |accessdate=4 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101218110537/http://www.nftsfilm-tv.ac.uk/index.php?module=People&type=Alumni&people_id=310&back=course&course_id=149 |archive-date=18 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.screenrush.co.uk/films/film-129567/casting/ |title=When I Was A Girl (TV)|publisher=Screen Rush |accessdate=14 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"DirectorandComposerCollaborations\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.filmscoremonthly.com/daily/article.cfm/articleID/6374/ |title=Current Composer/Director Partnerships, 2009 Edition |work=filmscoremonthly.com |publisher=Scott Bettencourt, Film Score Monthly |date=22 November 2009 |accessdate=14 March 2011 |quote=NICHOLAS HOOPER/DAVID YATES \"THE WEAVER'S WIFE\", \"GOOD LOOKS\" |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711002107/http://www.filmscoremonthly.com/daily/article.cfm/articleID/6374/ |archivedate=11 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.swindon.gov.uk/create |title=Arts and Culture, Create ... Harry Potter Connection |publisher=Swindon Borough Council |accessdate=15 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629053714/http://www.swindon.gov.uk/create |archivedate=29 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1994 to 1995, Yates directed several episodes of the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] police procedural ''[[The Bill]]'' before directing and producing three episodes of the television documentary ''Tale of Three Seaside Towns'' alongside producer Alistair Clarke. The programme followed media personalities [[Russell Grant]], [[Honor Blackman]] and [[Pam Ayres]] visiting and exploring the [[Southern England|South Coast]] towns of [[Brighton]], [[Eastbourne]] and [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/282 |title=The Tichborne Claimant |publisher=Philip Kemp, Sight and Sound |date=December 1999 |accessdate=14 March 2011 |quote=Yates, making his feature-film debut after directing television documentaries about British seaside towns... |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629071147/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/282 |archivedate=29 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myfairladythemusical.com/uk_cast_Blackman.htm|title=Cast & Creative ... Honor Blackman|publisher=My Fair Lady|accessdate=14 March 2011|quote=Honor presented a documentary for Workhouse TV/Meridian about Brighton which formed part of A TALE OF THREE SEASIDE TOWNS.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714142300/http://www.myfairladythemusical.com/uk_cast_Blackman.htm|archive-date=14 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Yates directed his fifth short film ''Punch'' before making his feature film debut in 1998 with the release of the independent historical-drama film ''[[The Tichborne Claimant (film)|The Tichborne Claimant]]''. The film, which was shown at the [[Edinburgh International Film Festival]], was written by Joe Fisher and based on the true events of the [[Tichborne Case]]. It starred [[Stephen Fry]] and [[Robert Hardy]] and was shot on location in [[Merseyside]] and on the [[Isle of Man]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/AFF066035 |title= PUNCH |publisher=British Board of Film Classification |date= 9 February 1996|accessdate=14 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.moviestation.org/movie/67407/The_Tichborne_Claimant |title= Movie: The Tichborne Claimant |publisher=Movie Station |accessdate=6 March 2011|quote=Filming Locations: Croxteth Hall, Croxteth, Liverpool, Merseyside, England, UK ... Isle of Man ... Liverpool, Merseyside, England, UK}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/AVF159003 |title= The tichborne claimant |publisher=British Board of Film Classification |date= 23 November 2000 |accessdate=14 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nYates returned to television in 2000 to direct the episodes of ''Greed'', ''Envy'' and ''Lust'' for the BBC miniseries ''[[The Sins]]'', starring [[Pete Postlethwaite]], as well as ''[[The Way We Live Now (2001 TV serial)|The Way We Live Now]]'', the four-part television adaptation of the [[The Way We Live Now|novel of the same name]] by [[Anthony Trollope]]. Yates shared the [[British Academy Television Awards#Categories|British Academy Television Award for Best Drama Serial]] with screenwriter [[Andrew Davies (writer)|Andrew Davies]] and producer [[Nigel Stafford-Clark]] at the [[British Academy Television Awards 2002|2002 BAFTA Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/nominations/?year=2002 |title=Past Winners and Nominees \u2013 Film \u2013 Awards \u2013 the BAFTA site, Film Nominations 2002 |publisher=British Academy of Film and Television Arts|accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nOne year later, Yates attended the [[56th British Academy Film Awards|56th BAFTA Awards]] with a [[BAFTA Award for Best Short Film|British Academy Film Award nomination for Best Short Film]] for the fourteen-minute production, ''[[Rank (film)|Rank]]'', which expressed the social elements of racism, friendship and adolescence through the story of a street gang that cross [[Glasgow]] to witness the arrival of a group of Somali refugees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.britfilms.com/britishfilms/catalogue/browse/?id=D9CC70591925b1964DGtH218B43F |title=The British Films Catalogue, Rank |publisher=Brit Films |accessdate=4 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061112235614/http://www.britfilms.com/britishfilms/catalogue/browse/?id=D9CC70591925b1964DGtH218B43F |archivedate=12 November 2006 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.film4.com/features/article/funding-your-short-film |title=Funding Your Short Film |publisher=Film4 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107032057/http://www.film4.com/features/article/funding-your-short-film |archivedate=7 November 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Yates said that even though ''The Way We Live Now'' was \"a very big production\" and \"enormous fun to do\", ''Rank'' was an opportunity to \"shake all that off\" and \"get back to [his] roots\". Of the casting, Yates said that he \"wanted to use non-actors to tell the story, to create a reality ... the kids we cast in Glasgow had never done a film before.\"<ref name=\"FilmLondon-DavidYates\"/> The film was noted for its gritty style and cinematography, with a review from ''Eye For Film'' stating that \"such intelligent use of camera and cast lifts Yates out of the pool of promising young directors into the front line of genuine hopefuls. This work demands respect.\"<ref name=\"NFTS-DavidYatesCourses\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eyeforfilm.co.uk/reviews.php?id=2278|title=Rank ... 4.5/5 stars|work=Angus Wolfe Murray, Eye for Film|accessdate=1 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe 2003 six-part thriller ''[[State of Play (TV serial)|State of Play]]'' was Yates's next achievement.<ref name=\"DavidYatesDoesItAll\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.moviemaker.com/directing/article/david_yates_harry_potter_and_the_half_blood_prince_20090708/ |title=David Yates Does It All |publisher=MovieMaker |date=9 July 2009 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130111074704/http://www.moviemaker.com/directing/article/david_yates_harry_potter_and_the_half_blood_prince_20090708/ |archivedate=11 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Yates collected the TV Spielfilm Award at the [[Cologne Conference]] in Germany and won the [[Directors Guild of Great Britain|Directors Guild of Great Britain Award]] for Outstanding Directorial Achievement.<ref name=\"DGA-DavidYatesDirectorProfile\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cologne-conference.de/en/meta/archive/2004/awardees  |title=TV Spielfilm Award 2004 \"State of Play\" by David Yates |publisher=Cologne Conference |accessdate=9 March 2011 |quote= This year's TV Spielfilm Award goes to David Yates' \"State of Play\". The Cologne Conference congratulates David Yates.}}</ref> The serial was recognised by various award ceremonies, receiving the [[Peabody Award]] for Broadcasting Excellence and being presented with two [[British Academy Television Craft Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/3720217.stm |title=State of Play wins craft Baftas |work=[[BBC]] |date=17 May 2004 |accessdate=1 August 2011}}</ref> The quality of the serial sparked Hollywood film bosses to consider [[State of Play (film)|adapting it into a film]], with producer [[Andrew Hauptman]] declaring that \"it's a blistering political thriller and we want to make an equally blistering movie.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4076367.stm  |title=Hollywood Calls for State of Play |work=BBC News   |date= 7 December 2004 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> ''State of Play'' is regarded by critics from ''[[The Guardian]]'' and ''[[The Times]]'' as one of the best British television dramas of the 2000s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.memorabletv.com/new/state-of-play.html |title=State of Play (BBC Drama series) DVD review |publisher=MemorableTV |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221054127/http://www.memorabletv.com/new/state-of-play.html |archivedate=21 February 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2010/jan/12/guardian-50-television-dramas  |title=The Guardian's top 50 television dramas of all time |work=The Guardian |location=London |author=Tim Lusher|date=12 January 2010|accessdate=7 March 2011|quote=Our TV critics have voted, debated and decided on a top 50 of classic TV drama series}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article6955835.ece  |title=The top 50 TV shows of the Noughties|work=The Times |location=UK |publisher=Andrew Billen, David Chater, Tim Teeman, Caitlin Moran.|date=19 December 2009|accessdate=7 March 2011|quote=Fists fly as The Times's frontline TV critics argue out the best 50 programmes of the decade |first=Greg |last=Hurst}}</ref>\n\nYates directed the television adaptation of nine-year-old [[Daisy Ashford]]'s novel ''[[The Young Visiters#Adaptations|The Young Visiters]]'', starring [[Jim Broadbent]] alongside [[Hugh Laurie]]. According to a review by [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']] magazine for [[BBC America]], Yates and his team yielded \"a warm and surprisingly unsentimental production that has 'evergreen' written all over it\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117925407?refCatId=32  |title=The Young Visiters (Movie \u2013 BBC America; Wednesday, Nov.&nbsp;3, 8 p.m.) |work=Variety   |date= 31 October 2004 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |first=Brian |last=Lowry}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Yates's two-part drama ''[[Sex Traffic]]'' was broadcast on [[Channel 4]]. It won eight BAFTA Awards including [[BAFTA Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]] for [[Mark Day (editor)|Mark Day]], who regularly worked with Yates on many of his television projects and short films. Day commented on his collaboration with Yates saying that \"we are very good friends because we have spent so much time together\". He also said, \"David shoots in a similar style from piece to piece, although this wasn\u2019t quite as frantic as ''State of Play''.\"<ref name=\"EditorWinsBAFTA\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/s/52439_editor_wins_his_second_consecutive_bafta_award_over_campaigning_drama  |title=Editor wins his second consecutive BAFTA award over campaigning drama |publisher=Get Surrey |date= 19 May 2005 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> Yates was nominated for another Directors Guild of Great Britain Award for his direction of ''Sex Traffic'' and won his second BAFTA for Best Drama Serial at the British Academy Television Awards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bafta.org/awards-database.html?year=2004&category=Television&award=Drama+Serial  |title=Awards Database \u2013 The BAFTA site |publisher=BAFTA (bafta.org) |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> Being a British-Canadian production, ''Sex Traffic'' gained four wins at Canada's annual television award ceremony, the [[Gemini Award]]s, including Best Dramatic Mini-Series. Spanning across two parts, the three-hour-long drama reveals how the [[Human trafficking|trafficking of young women]] into slavery is a big business which operates throughout Europe; both parts were acclaimed for their \"shocking\" portrayal of such a sensitive topic.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/AVV227775  |title=BBFC ... Sex Traffic |publisher=British Board of Film Classification |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/1277745/ |title=BFI ScreenOnline: Sex Traffic (2004) |author=Neil Sinyard |publisher=BFI ScreenOnline |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ifcfilms.com/films/sex-traffic |title=About Sex Traffic |work=IFC Films |accessdate=4 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707113746/http://www.ifcfilms.com/films/sex-traffic |archivedate=7 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2004, Yates was involved in plans for a film adaptation of [[Evelyn Waugh]]'s novel ''[[Brideshead Revisited]]'' for [[Warner Independent Pictures]]. He was set to work with [[Paul Bettany]], [[Jude Law]] and [[Jennifer Connelly]] on the project, but pulled out in the later stages due to constant budget issues affecting the film's production.<ref name=\"DarkHorizons-DavidYatesBridesheadRevisited&HBP\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.darkhorizons.com/features/1448/david-yates-for-harry-potter-and-the-half-blood-prince  |title=Exclusive Interview: David Yates for \"Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince\" |publisher=Paul Fischer, Dark Horizons |date= 13 July 2009 |accessdate=4 March 2011| quote=He had been developing a version of Evelyn Waugh's novel, Brideshead Revisited in 2004 for the studio's art house division, Warner Independent Pictures, with husband-and-wife actors Paul Bettany and Jennifer Connolly negotiating to play the leads, but after finally landing the highly coveted \"Potter\" job and with budget issues stalling \"Brideshead,\" Yates transitioned into his new assignment.}}</ref><ref name=\"VarietyReviewsBrideshead\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117937762?refcatid=31  |title=Variety Reviews: Brideshead Revisited |work=Variety   |date=18 July 2008 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |quote=Reportedly, Paul Bettany, Jude Law and Jennifer Connelly were attached until helmer David Yates was poached for last year's \"Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix.\" One can say, in this case, that settling for the B team turned out well. |first=Dennis |last=Harvey}}</ref>\n\nYates then directed [[Richard Curtis]]' script to ''[[The Girl in the Caf\u00e9]]'', a television film starring [[Bill Nighy]] and [[Kelly Macdonald]]. In June 2005, the film was aired on the BBC in Britain and was also broadcast in the United States on [[HBO|Home Box Office]]. ''The Girl in the Caf\u00e9'' achieved three wins at the [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]s, including the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Made for Television Movie]], and gained a total of four nominations including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Miniseries, Movie or a Dramatic Special|Outstanding Directing]] for Yates.<ref name=\"Yahoo!Movies-DavidYatesBio\"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://movies.msn.com/celebrities/celebrity-awards-and-nominations/david-yates.1/ |title=David Yates \u2013 Awards & Nominations (Emmy Award) |publisher=MSN Movies |accessdate=4 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119021642/http://movies.msn.com/celebrities/celebrity-awards-and-nominations/david-yates.1/ |archive-date=19 January 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000223/2006  |title=Emmy Awards for 2006 |website=IMDb  |date= 19 August 2006 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n===''Harry Potter'' (2006\u20132011)===\n[[File:David Yates.jpg|thumb|left|Yates outside [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] at the premiere of ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]'' on 8 July 2007]]\nDuring the period of working on plans for ''Brideshead Revisited'', Yates was told by his agent that he had made the director shortlist for the fifth film in the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' series]]. He was then confirmed to direct ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]'' by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]], with production scheduled to begin in early 2006.<ref name=\"VarietyReviewsBrideshead\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hpana.com/news.18428.html  |title=David Yates confirms 'Order of the Phoenix' role |publisher=HPANA (source: This is Wiltshire) |date=29 November 2004 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> When asked how Yates got the job, producer [[David Heyman]] (\"a big fan\" of Yates's television work)<ref name=\"TheObserver-DavidYatesinterview\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2007/jun/24/harrypotter  |title=How I raised Potter's bar |work=The Observer |location=London |author=Amy Raphael |date=24 June 2007 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |quote= Without wishing to sound rude, how did he get the job? 'You're not the first to ask,' he laughs...}}</ref> said that \"actors in David's television projects give their best performance, often of their career. It's important to keep pushing the actors, particularly the young ones on each ''Potter'' film. This is a political film, not with a capital P, but it's about teen rebellion and the abuse of power. David has made films in the U.K. about politics without being heavy handed.\"<ref name=\"HeymanYatesOOTP\">{{cite news |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117968266?refcatid=1288 |title=WB Wild For Harry Potter |work=Variety |date=9 July 2007 |accessdate=15 June 2011 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro}}</ref>\n\nBefore production began, Yates invited ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]'' director [[Mike Newell (director)|Mike Newell]] to a pub and \"picked his brains about what it was going to be like to step into someone's shoes on a movie of this scale\".<ref name=\"DGA-DavidYatesDirectorProfile\"/> The first scene that Yates shot featured a [[Giant (mythology)|giant]] interacting with human characters. The scene was the very first high-scale [[visual effects]] piece Yates filmed in his career.<ref name=\"DGA-DavidYatesDirectorProfile\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2010/exclusive-interview-harry-potter-series-producer-david-heyman/  |title=Exclusive Interview: 'Harry Potter' Producer David Heyman |author=Alex Billington |publisher=FirstShowing.net |date=9 December 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> After the film's post-production material was well received by the studio, Yates was chosen to direct the sixth film, ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'', which according to Yates was going to be \"a cross between the chills of ''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (film)|Prisoner of Azkaban]]'' [the third film in the series] and the fantastical adventure of ''Goblet of Fire''\".<ref name=\"VirginMedia-DavidYates\"/><ref name=\"DarkHorizons-DavidYatesBridesheadRevisited&HBP\"/>\n\nIn 2007, ''Order of the Phoenix'' opened to positive reviews and commercial success. Yates won the title of [[Empire Award for Best Director|Best Director]] at the [[Empire Awards]] and collected the [[European Film Academy People's Choice Award for Best European Film|People's Choice Award]] from the [[European Film Academy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.europeanfilmacademy.org/The-Peoples-Choice-Awards-Winners.60.0.html |title=European Film Awards, 2008 |publisher=European Film Academy |date= 6 December 2008 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> However, the film was criticised by fans of the series for having the shortest running time out of the five released instalments; Yates said that the original director's cut was \"probably over three hours\", resulting in much footage being cut, condensed and edited to fit within the studio's preferred time frame.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2006/10/27/ootp-director-david-yates-i-ve-shot-a-movie-that-s-probably-over-three-hours |title=OotP Director David Yates: \"I've Shot a Movie That's Probably Over Three Hours\" |author=Sue Upton |publisher=The Leaky Cauldron |work=Empire Magazine |date= 27 October 2006 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/harry-potter-and-the-order-of-phoenix-shortened-to-avoid-grindhouse-failure/ |title=Harry Potter and The Order of Phoenix Shortened to Avoid Grindhouse Failure? |author=Peter Sciretta |publisher=SlashFilm |date= 13 April 2007 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring production of ''Half-Blood Prince'', Warner Bros. executive [[Alan F. Horn]] announced that the seventh and final novel in the series, ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]'', was to be split into two cinematic parts with Yates, once again, as the director.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/movies/la-et-potter13mar13,0,7162166.story |title=Final 'Harry Potter' book will be split into two movies |author=Geoff Boucher |work=Los Angeles Times |date= 13 March 2008 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> Yates spoke of the decision to appoint him as the director of the final films, remarking that \"they wanted to do a ''Harry Potter'' that felt ... more grown up. What's smart about the studio and the producers is they have always wanted to push it a bit. [[Chris Columbus (filmmaker)|Chris Columbus]] did a wonderful job of casting and making this world incredibly popular. But rather than do more of the same, they said, 'Let's bring in [[Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n]] and let him run with it. Then later, let's bring in David Yates, who's done all this hard-hitting stuff on TV.' It's a testament to their ambition to try to keep the franchise fresh. The bizarre thing is, I did one [film] and they asked me to stay for three more, so obviously they liked something.\"<ref name=\"DGA-DavidYatesDirectorProfile\"/>\n\n''Half-Blood Prince'' was released in 2009 and became the only film in the series to earn an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/harry_potter_and_the_half_blood_prince/news/1831803/tomatometer_watch_how_good_is_harry_potter_and_the_half_blood_prince |title=Tomatometer Watch: How Good is Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince? |publisher=Jen Yamato, Rotten Tomatoes |date= 10 July 2009 |accessdate=6 March 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/2009-academy-award-nominations-announced/ |title=82nd Annual Academy Award Nominations Announced |author=Russ Fischer |publisher=Slash Film |date=2 February 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2011 }}</ref> Yates worked alongside French cinematographer [[Bruno Delbonnel]] on, what Yates called, extensively colour grading the \"incredibly rich\" picture by making it look \"very European\" and drawing influences from the Dutch painter [[Rembrandt]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/harry-potter-and-the-half-blood-prince-3/page:3 |title=Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince ... We go on set for the latest Potter picture |magazine=Total Film |date=1 April 2009|accessdate=7 March 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Film-Review/harry-potter-the-half-blood-prince-david-yates-interview |title=Harry Potter & The Half-Blood Prince \u2013 David Yates interview |publisher=IndieLondon |accessdate=6 March 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/112/1125648p1.html |title=Harry Potter: The Journey Ends Here |author=Orlando Parfitt |publisher=IGN Movies |date=5 October 2010 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713004816/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/112/1125648p1.html |archivedate=13 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The film garnered a mix of accolades and was acclaimed for its stylised character-driven approach, but some fans complained about the script's deviation from the novel and the film's slight [[romantic comedy]] nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/harry_potter_and_the_half_blood_prince/news/1832250/rt_interview_david_yates_on_harry_potter_and_the_half_blood_prince |title=RT Interview: David Yates on Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince |author=Joe Utichi |website=Rotten Tomatoes |date=15 July 2009 |accessdate=6 March 2011 |quote=Includes fan comments}}</ref> In response to this criticism, renowned BAFTA member and film critic [[Mark Kermode]] praised Yates's direction and ranked the film \"second best\" in the series, behind ''Prisoner of Azkaban''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02n9kzh |title=Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince reviewed by Mark Kermode |publisher=BBC Radio 5 Live |date=16 November 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2011 |quote=This is the second best Harry Potter film.}}</ref>\n\nYates [[Production of Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows|began to film]] ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1|Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1]]'' and ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2|Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2]]'' back-to-back in early 2009 and finished reshoots in late 2010.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://filmonic.com/deathly-hallows-epilogue-scenes-to-be-reshot-over-christmas |title=Deathly Hallows epilogue scenes to be reshot over Christmas |work=Filmonic |date=13 November 2010 |accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> He stated that he had shot the two parts of the final adaptation differently, with Part 1 being a \"[[road movie]]\" and \"quite real\", \"almost like a [[Cin\u00e9ma v\u00e9rit\u00e9|v\u00e9rit\u00e9]] documentary\", while Part 2 is \"more operatic, colourful and [[fantasy film|fantasy-oriented]]\", a \"big opera with huge battles.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nationalpost.com/todays-paper/Harry+Potter+last+goodbye/3848043/story.html |title=Harry Potter & the last goodbye |publisher=Bob Thompson, Postmedia News |date=18 November 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2011 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.filmschoolrejects.com/news/if-the-harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-two-film-adaptation-were-a-person-this-splitting-point-would-be-the-taint.php |title=If The Two Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows Films Were A Person This Would Be The Perineum |publisher=Rob Hunter, Film School Rejects |date=13 August 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623214612/http://www.filmschoolrejects.com/news/if-the-harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-two-film-adaptation-were-a-person-this-splitting-point-would-be-the-taint.php |archivedate=23 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.the-leaky-cauldron.org/2010/1/24/david-yates-deathly-hallows-a-big-opera-a-great-big-epic-with-huge-battles |title=David Yates: \"Deathly Hallows\" a \"big opera, a great big epic, with huge battles\" |publisher=Edward, The Leaky Cauldron (source: Total Film Magazine)|date=24 January 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> Yates reshot the final scene of the ''Harry Potter'' series at [[Warner Bros. Studios, Leavesden|Leavesden Studios]] after the original version, filmed at [[London King's Cross railway station]], did not meet his expectations. In the film, the scene takes place at the magical [[Platform 9\u00be]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://screenrant.com/harry-potter-deathly-hallows-epilogue-sirius-scorpius-actors-benk-93896/ |title=Harry Potter's 'Deathly Hallows' Epilogue Reshoot Complete; Adds 'Severus' Child-Actor |work=Ben Kendrick at Screenrant |date=December 2010 |accessdate=9 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nPart 1 was released worldwide in November 2010 to commercial success along with generally positive reviews, some of which reflected on Yates's directing style. ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' affirmed that \"David Yates' fluid, fast-paced direction sends up the crackling tension of a thriller\" and ''[[The New York Times]]'' analysed Yates's approach to J. K. Rowling's character development by saying that he has \"demonstrated a thorough, uncondescending sympathy for her characters, in particular the central trio of [[Ron Weasley]], [[Hermione Granger]] and [[Harry Potter (character)|Harry Potter]] himself.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.casarotto.co.uk/news/david-yates-harry-potter-breaks-box-office-records-12330 |title=David Yates' Harry Potter breaks Box Office records |publisher=Casarotto (source: BBC News) |date=23 November 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807145729/http://www.casarotto.co.uk/news/david-yates-harry-potter-breaks-box-office-records-12330 |archive-date=7 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2010/11/19/movies/19harry.html|title=Time for Young Wizards to Put Away Childish Things |author=A. O. Scott |work=The New York Times |date=18 November 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref> The film was praised for its \"dark\" atmosphere and its loyalty to the source material, but it was criticised for its slow middle act, the handling of exposition, and the somewhat disjointed pacing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/harry_potter_and_the_deathly_hallows_part_i/ |title=Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows Part 1 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/71686,news-comment,entertainment,what-theyre-saying-about-harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-part-1|title=What they're saying about the new Harry Potter film |author=Natalie Davies |magazine=The First Post |date=20 November 2010 |accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nPart 2 was screened in July 2011 and became an instant record-breaking success with critical acclaim.<ref name=\"DH2RT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/harry_potter_and_the_deathly_hallows_part_ii/ |title=Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part II (2011) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"DH2MC\">{{cite news| url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-part-2 |title=Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part 2 |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=15 July 2011}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' described Part 2 as \"monumental cinema awash with gorgeous tones\" and ''[[Total Film]]'' wrote that Yates combines \"spectacle and emotion into a thrilling final chapter.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/harry-potter/8619487/Harry-Potter-and-the-Deathly-Hallow-Part-2-review.html |title=Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows, Part 2, review |author=Philip Womack |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date= 6 July 2011 |accessdate=6 July 2011 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/reviews/cinema/harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-part-2?ns_campaign=reviews&ns_mchannel=rss&ns_source=totalfilm&ns_linkname=0&ns_fee=0 |title=Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part 2 |work=[[Total Film]] |date=7 July 2011 |accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref> Author J. K. Rowling remarked that \"everyone who watches ''Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2'' is going to see that he's steered us home magnificently. It's incredible.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.movies.yahoo.com/blog/article/221834/harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-part-2reviewed.html |title=Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part 2 \u2013 reviewed |work=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |date=8 July 2011 |accessdate=9 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711134618/http://uk.movies.yahoo.com/blog/article/221834/harry-potter-and-the-deathly-hallows-part-2reviewed.html |archivedate=11 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/markkermode/2011/07/wild_about_harry.html |title=Wild About Harry |work=[[BBC]] |date=15 July 2011 |accessdate=16 July 2011}}</ref> Part 2 is the only ''Harry Potter'' film to pass the $1 billion mark during its original theatrical run; it became the [[List of highest-grossing films#Worldwide highest-grossing films|highest-grossing]] film in the series and the highest-grossing film of 2011, making Yates the director of the highest-grossing non-[[James Cameron]] film of all time in August 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110731005089/en/%E2%80%9CHarry-Potter-Deathly-Hallows-%E2%80%93-Part-2%E2%80%9D |title=\"Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2\" Crosses $1 Billion Threshold |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=31 July 2011 |accessdate=31 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/harry-potter-deathly-hallows-part-220419 |title='Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows Part 2' Becomes No. 3 Film of All Time at Box Office |work=Pamela McClintock, [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=8 August 2011 |accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> Amongst other accolades, Yates won his second Empire Award for Best Director and joined the principal creative team of ''Harry Potter'' in receiving the 2012 [[ADG Excellence in Production Design Award|ADG Award for Outstanding Contribution to Cinematic Imagery]] for their work on ''Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2'' and the series in general.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118045381 |title=ADG to fete 'Harry Potter' creative team |date=1 November 2011 |accessdate=14 December 2011 |work=Variety |first=Dave |last=McNary}}</ref>\n\nYates attended the [[64th British Academy Film Awards]] in February 2011, where he was joined by J. K. Rowling, David Heyman, Mike Newell, Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n, [[David Barron (film producer)|David Barron]], [[Rupert Grint]], and [[Emma Watson]] in collecting the [[64th British Academy Film Awards#Michael Balcon Award for Outstanding British Contribution to Cinema|Michael Balcon Award for Outstanding British Contribution to Cinema]] on behalf of the ''Harry Potter'' films. [[Daniel Radcliffe]], who portrayed the films' titular character, commented on working with Yates, saying that he \"added his own sense of grit and realism [to the series] that perhaps wasn't there so much before. I think we all had a fantastic time working with David. I know we did.\"<ref name=\"DavidYatesEarlyLifeBAFTA\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Film-Review/harry-potter-the-order-of-the-phoenix-daniel-radcliffe-interview |title=Daniel Radcliffe interview |publisher=IndieLondon |accessdate=9 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Subsequent work (2012\u2013present)===\nBy 2012, Yates was working on a few [[Warner Bros.]] projects, including a ''Tarzan'' feature film and an [[Al Capone]] biopic called ''Cicero''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.totalfilm.com/news/tom-hardy-attached-to-play-al-capone-in-a-david-yates-cicero |title=Tom Hardy attached to play Al Capone in a David Yates' Cicero |work=[[Total Film]] |accessdate=19 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2012/11/david-yates-committing-to-tarzan-at-warner-bros.html?MID=TWITTER_VULTURE|title=David Yates Committing to Tarzan at Warner Bros. -- Vulture|author=Claude Brodesser-Akner|work=Vulture}}</ref> He also controversially said that he was working with [[BBC Worldwide]] on plans to develop a ''[[Doctor Who]]'' film,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://collider.com/doctor-who-movie-david-yates/126358/ |title=David Yates to Direct DOCTOR WHO Movie |date=14 November 2011 |accessdate=15 November 2011}}</ref> although this was denied by the showrunner, [[Steven Moffat]], in July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/07/30/doctor-who-steven-moffat-2/|title='Doctor Who' film rumors 'a weird fantasy'|work=Entertainment Weekly's EW.com}}</ref> Because of production delays, Yates began to explore other projects including television work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/04/tarzan-dying-on-the-vine-at-warner-bros/|title='Tarzan' Dying On The Vine At Warner Bros? - Deadline|author=Mike Fleming Jr|work=Deadline}}</ref>\n\n[[File:David Yates (27996598333).jpg|thumb|right|Yates speaking at [[San Diego Comic-Con|San Diego Comic-Con International]], 2016]]\nIn 2013, he returned to television by signing on to direct the [[television pilot]] of ''[[Tyrant (TV series)|Tyrant]]'', an American drama production set against the US\u2013Middle East conflict.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/harry-potters-david-yates-direct-567654 | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Lacey | last=Rose | title=Harry Potter's' David Yates to Direct FX Drama Pilot 'Tyrant | date=12 June 2013}}</ref> The following year, Yates began shooting ''[[The Legend of Tarzan (film)|The Legend of Tarzan]]'', starring [[Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd]], [[Samuel L. Jackson]], [[Margot Robbie]], [[Djimon Hounsou]], [[Jim Broadbent]], and [[Christoph Waltz]]. The film, released in 2016, opened to mixed reviews and a worldwide total of $356.7 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=tarzan2016.htm |title=The Legend of Tarzan (2016) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nYates directed ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]'', a 2016 film which is the first in a series of five instalments based on J. K. Rowling's book, set in the world of her ''Harry Potter'' novels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hypable.com/2014/10/15/fantastic-beasts-director-david-yates/|title=WB names David Yates 'Fantastic Beasts' director|work=Hypable}}</ref> David Heyman and ''Harry Potter'' screenwriter [[Steve Kloves]] joined Yates and J. K. Rowling in developing the script.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.themarysue.com/heyman-fantastic-beasts-fables/|title = X-Men's Jane Goldman Joining Fables Film Writing Team, Updates on Rowling's Fantastic Beasts|date = 20 January 2015|accessdate = 20 January 2015|website = The Mary Sue}}</ref> The film was released in November 2016, it received generally positive reviews and was a commercial  success having grossed $814 million , The film stars [[Eddie Redmayne]], [[Katherine Waterston]], [[Dan Fogler]], [[Alison Sudol]], [[Ezra Miller]], [[Colin Farrell]], and [[Johnny Depp]]. Yates directed the 2018 sequel, ''[[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]'' which received mixed critical reception but emerged a box office success having grossed $654 million. In an interview with ''The Hollywood Reporter'', he stated he was open to directing all five planned films in the ''Fantastic Beasts'' series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/fantastic-beasts-david-yates-says-hes-directing-all-five-films-946671|title=David Yates Says He's Directing All Five 'Fantastic Beasts' Films|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2016-11-12}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYates has a younger brother and an elder sister.<ref name=\"DavidYatesCollider2011\"/> He is married to Yvonne Walcott.<ref name=Star>{{cite news |author=Simon Mulligan |url=https://www.sthelensstar.co.uk/news/15105128.harry-potter-director-david-yates-named-citizen-of-honour-at-liverpool-city-hall/ |title=Harry Potter director David Yates named Citizen of Honour at Liverpool City Hall |newspaper=St Helens Star |date=21 February 2017 |accessdate=28 June 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Directing style==\n[[Emma Watson]] stated that Yates liked to push the cast and crew to physical and emotional extremes, with [[Gary Oldman]] confirming Yates's preference for working slowly by shooting numerous [[take]]s to draw the best performances out of the cast.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a287844/emma-watson-cried-at-director-yates.html |title=Emma Watson 'cried at director Yates' |work=[[Digital Spy]] |date=15 November 2010 |accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.metro.co.uk/film/865710-gary-oldman-im-not-sad-about-the-end-of-harry-potter |title=Gary Oldman: I'm not sad about the end of Harry Potter| work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date= 8 June 2011 |accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> Yates has been influenced by such directors as [[Steven Spielberg]], [[David Lean]], and [[Ken Loach]].<ref name=\"FilmLondon-DavidYates\">{{Cite news|url=http://filmlondon.org.uk/news/2007/december/david_yates_on_harry_potter |title=David Yates on Harry Potter|publisher=Film London |date=23 December 2007 |accessdate=11 March 2011}}</ref> Yates's style of work includes social and political themes, character-driven narratives, realism, and atmospheric drama.<ref name=\"DavidYatesBaltimore2\">{{cite news |url=http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/movies/blog/2011/06/brush_up_on_harry_potter_at_ho.html |title=Brush up on Harry Potter at Hopkins and Lakefront Film Festivals |work=Baltimore Sun |date= 10 June 2011|accessdate=14 June 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emanuellevy.com/comment/harry-potters-new-director-david-yates-6/ |title=Harry Potter's New Director David Yates |work=Emanuel Levy (cinema 24/7) |accessdate=21 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322054822/http://www.emanuellevy.com/comment/harry-potters-new-director-david-yates-6/ |archive-date=22 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"David Yates RTV\">{{cite news |url=http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20090710/david-yates-director-que-pone-punto-final-saga-harry-potter/284476.shtml |title=David Yates, the director who puts an end to saga of 'Harry Potter' |work=RTV.es |date=10 July 2009 |accessdate=21 June 2011 |quote= His work is defined by the use of political and social elements ... expertise to address specific issues such as corruption...}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n=== Feature films ===\n* ''[[The Tichborne Claimant (film)|The Tichborne Claimant]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 2]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[The Legend of Tarzan (film)|The Legend of Tarzan]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]'' (2018)\n* ''Fantastic Beasts 3'' (2021)\n* ''Fantastic Beasts 4'' (TBA)\n* ''Fantastic Beasts 5'' (TBA)\n\n=== Short films ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Director\n![[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n!Producer\n|-\n|1988\n|''When I Was a Girl''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1991\n|''The Weaver's Wife''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|-\n|''Oranges and Lemons''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n|-\n|1992\n|''Good Looks''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n|-\n|1996\n|''Punch''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Rank (film)|Rank]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Director\n!Producer\n!Episode(s)\n!Notes\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Moving Pictures (TV series)|Moving Pictures]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|<nowiki>''Low Budget''</nowiki>\n| TV Series documentary\n|-\n|1994-95\n|''[[The Bill]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|<nowiki>''Death and Taxes'', ''Full Contact'', ''Life's a Bitch''</nowiki>, <nowiki>''Feeling Guilty'', ''Other Voice''</nowiki>\n|TV Series\n|-\n|1995\n| ''Tale of Three Seaside Towns''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|All 3 episodes <small>(co-directing with Alistair Clarke)</small>\n| TV Series documentary\n|-\n| 2000\n|''[[The Sins]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|<nowiki>''</nowiki>Lust<nowiki>''</nowiki>, <nowiki>''</nowiki>Envy<nowiki>''</nowiki>, <nowiki>''</nowiki>Greed<nowiki>''</nowiki>\n| TV Mini-Series\n|-\n| 2001\n|''[[The Way We Live Now (2001 TV serial)|The Way We Live Now]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|All 4 episodes\n|TV Mini-Series\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2003\n|''[[State of Play (TV serial)|State of Play]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|All 6 episodes\n|TV Mini-Series\n|-\n|''[[The Young Visiters]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 2004\n|''[[Sex Traffic]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|All 2 episodes\n| TV Mini-Series\n|-\n| 2005\n|''[[The Girl in the Caf\u00e9]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|{{n/a}}\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 2014\n|''[[Tyrant (TV series)|Tyrant]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes|Executive}}\n|<nowiki>''Pilot''</nowiki>\n| TV Series\n|-\n|}\n\n==Accolades==\n''Only certain awards for Yates's direction are shown in this section. A complete list of awards for a project may be found on its article page.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Award \n! Category\n! Title\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1991\n| [[Cork Film Festival|Cork International Film Festival]]\n| Best European Short\n| ''When I Was a Girl''\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[San Francisco International Film Festival]]:<br />[[San Francisco International Film Festival#Golden Gate Awards|Golden Gate Award]]<br />\n| Best Short Film\n| ''When I Was a Girl''\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Belfort Film Festival\n| Best Film\n| 